ch were called <i>Schermaus</i> in Switzerland."],"variants":[{"name":"Moser","meanings":["South German and Swiss German: topographic name for someone who lived near a peat bog, Middle High German <i>mōs</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place named with this word. Compare   Mosser   and   Musser  .","North German (<b>Möser</b>): metonymic occupational name for a vegetable grower or seller, from an agent noun based on Middle Low German <i>mōs</i> ‘vegetable’.","German (<b>Möser</b>): habitational name from any of several places called Möser, or for someone from any of several places called Möse, Moese, and Mösen."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290